    {
      "turn_number": 18,
      "role": "persona",
      "type": "response",
      "text": "I keep reading because my brain wants to know every danger so I can maybe stop it. My hands get cold, my heart racing like when I first found out I was pregnant. I imagine each story happening to me in that bright hospital room where I will be alone, and the pictures in my head get louder than my breathing.\n\nAfter a while I close the phone and feel stupid for reading—like I invited the fear. But I also feel a strange control: at least I know what can go wrong. I try to turn it into something useful. I write a list of questions for my next appointment, simple things in Spanish and English: “What are my pain options?” “Can someone translate?” I also force myself to do small things to calm down—cook, drink chamomile, call my sister back home even if the time is wrong. Sometimes I leave a message in the clinic portal asking for a midwife who speaks Spanish. It doesn’t fix the fear, but it makes me feel less alone.",
      "responding_to_question_id": "Q8",
      "input_tokens": 1143,
      "output_tokens": 469
    },
